'''Johan Felipe Vásquez Ibarra''' (born 22 October 1998) is a Mexican professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[centre-back]] for {{Italian football updater|Genoa}} club [[Genoa CFC|Genoa]], which he [[captain (association football)|captains]], and the [[Mexico national football team|Mexico national team]].

==Club career==
===Sonora===
Vásquez first joined [[Tigres UANL|Tigres UANL youth academy]] in 2015. He then briefly transferred to [[Tercera División de México]] club Poblado Miguel Alemán FC in 2016 before settling in [[Cimarrones de Sonora]], successfully going through the ranks until reaching the first team and making his professional debut in the [[Ascenso MX]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Johan Vásquez|url=https://ligamx.net/cancha/jugador/111222/eyJpZENsdWIiOiAxNH0=/johan-felipe-vasquez-ibarra|website=ligamx.net|accessdate=2 September 2017|language=es-MX}}</ref><ref>https://www.mural.com.mx/tigres-rayados-el-camino-de-johan-vasquez-a-jjoo/ar2154129</ref>

===Monterrey===
In April 2018, Vásquez joined [[C.F. Monterrey|Monterrey]] on a two-year loan deal with the option to buy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Johan Vásquez, nuevo jugador de Rayados|date=18 April 2018|url=https://www.multimedios.com/deportes/futbol/rayados/johan-vasquez-nuevo-jugador-rayados.html}}</ref> He was eventually purchased by Monterrey for [[US$]]2 million, making him the most expensive transfer between the top two levels of Mexican football.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cimarrones de Sonora, una cantera para la Liga MX|date=20 May 2021|url=https://www.futboltotal.com.mx/futbol-mexicano/liga-mx/cimarrones-de-sonora-una-cantera-para-la-liga-mx/2021/05}}</ref>

===UNAM===
In December 2019, following a lack of playing time, Vásquez joined [[Club Universidad Nacional|UNAM]] on loan with the option to buy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Johan Vásquez llegará a Pumas UNAM con un préstamo a dos años con opción a compra|date=23 December 2019 |url=https://dalepumas.bolavip.com/ligamx/Johan-Vasquez-llegara-a-Pumas-UNAM-con-un-prestamo-a-dos-anos-con-opcion-a-compra-20191223-0005.html}}</ref> On 12 January 2020, he made his debut with the team, appearing in the starting line up against [[C.F. Pachuca|Pachuca]] as the ''Pumas'' won 2–1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://espndeportes.espn.com/futbol/reporte/_/juegoId/561965|title=UNAM 2-1 Pachuca (12 de Ene., 2020) Análisis del partido|website=ESPN DEPORTES}}</ref> Two months later, following impressive performances, 50 percent of his rights were purchased by UNAM.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pumas habría comprado parte de la carta de Johan Vásquez|work=Soy Fútbol |url=https://www.soyfutbol.com/ligas/Pumas-habria-comprado-parte-de-la-carta-de-Johan-Vasquez-20200221-0032.html}}</ref>

He solidified his place in the starting eleven, helping the team reach the [[Guardianes 2020 Liga MX championship stage#Finals|Guardianes 2020 championship finals]], losing against [[Club León|León]] in an aggregate 3–1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dalepumas.bolavip.com/noticias/Los-5-mejores-jugadores-de-Pumas-UNAM-en-2020--Liga-MX---Clausura-2020-y-Guard1anes-2020-20201216-0008.html|title=Los 5 mejores jugadores de Pumas UNAM en 2020}}</ref> He was subsequently included in the tournament's best XI.<ref>{{cite web|title=Liga MX: León, Pumas y Cruz Azul se 'roban' el 11 ideal del Guardianes 2020|url=https://www.soyfutbol.com/ligas/Liga-MX-Leon-Pumas-y-Cruz-Azul-se-roban-el-11-ideal-del-Guardianes-2020-20201216-0041.html|work=SoyFutbol.com|language=Spanish|first=Luis|last=De la Cruz|date=16 December 2020}}</ref>

===Genoa===
====2021–22: Debut season====
On 16 August 2021, Vásquez joined [[Serie A]] club [[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa]] on a season-long loan with an obligation to buy after one played match for a transfer fee of €3.5 million.<ref>{{cite news|title=Johan Vásquez es oficialmente nuevo jugador del Genoa de la Serie A.|url=https://www.marca.com/claro-mx/futbol/mexicanos-mundo/2021/08/16/611a6b70e2704e4a7f8b45bc.html|publisher=Marca Claro|date=16 August 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://espndeportes.espn.com/futbol/italia/nota/_/id/9041955/johan-vasquez-genoa-viaje-italia-europa | title=Johan Vásquez viaja a Italia para cerrar su fichaje con el Genoa | date=11 August 2021 }}</ref> On 17 October, Vásquez made his debut with the team in a league match against [[U.S. Sassuolo Calcio|Sassuolo]], scoring the equalizing goal for his team for a 2–2 draw.<ref>{{cite web|title=Johan Vásquez, el 'nómada' del futbol mexicano que cumple su sueño en Italia al debutar con un gol|date=18 October 2021 |url=https://espndeportes.espn.com/futbol/italia/nota/_/id/9374440/johan-vasquez-gol-debut-genoa-nomada-liga-mx-historia}}</ref>

====2022–23: Loan to Cremonese====
On 18 June 2022, Vásquez moved to recently promoted [[U.S. Cremonese|Cremonese]] on loan with an option to buy.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Cremonese|url=https://www.uscremonese.it/johan-vasquez-e-un-nuovo-giocatore-della-cremonese/|title=JOHAN VASQUEZ È UN NUOVO GIOCATORE DELLA CREMONESE|date=18 June 2022|access-date=20 June 2022|language=it|archive-date=22 June 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220622170331/https://www.uscremonese.it/johan-vasquez-e-un-nuovo-giocatore-della-cremonese/|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 6 May 2023, Vásquez scored Cremonese's second goal in a 2–0 victory over [[Spezia Calcio|Spezia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tudn.com/futbol/serie-a/johan-vasquez-anota-y-el-cremonese-logra-triunfo-vital-en-la-serie-a|title=Johan Vásquez anota y el Cremonese logra un triunfo vital en la Serie A &#124; TUDN Serie A &#124; TUDN|website=www.tudn.com}}</ref> He returned to Genoa after the end of the [[2022–23 Serie A|season]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/serie-a/johan-vasquez-permaneceria-serie-proxima-campana-genoa | title=Johan Vásquez seguiría con Genoa en la Serie a italiana | date=14 June 2023 }}</ref>

On 22 February 2024, Vásquez renewed his contract with Genoa, extending it through 2027.<ref>https://espndeportes.espn.com/futbol/italia/nota/_/id/13269262/johan-vasquez-renovo-con-genoa-hasta-2027</ref>

====2024–25: Player of the season====
On 13 April 2025, Vásquez made his 121st league appearance in a scoreless draw against [[Hellas Verona]], surpassing [[Hirving Lozano]] as the Mexican with the most appearances in Serie A.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://mexico.as.com/futbol/mexicanos-por-el-mundo/johan-vasquez-un-historico-de-serie-a-n/ | title=Johan Vásquez, un histórico de Serie A }}</ref> On 11 May, in his 100th Serie A appearance with Genoa, he scored the equalizing goal in 2–2 away draw against [[SSC Napoli|Napoli]].<ref>https://www.tudn.com/futbol/serie-a/johan-vasquez-marca-golazo-y-el-genoa-logra-empate-ante-napoli</ref> On 19 May, he was awarded the club's "Grifone d'Oro" for best player of the season.<ref name="Genoa">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/serie-a/johan-vasquez-reconocido-mvp-temporada-genoa|title=Johan Vásquez, reconocido como MVP de la temporada con el Genoa|first=Sebastián|last=Faed|date=17 August 2025|website=Mediotiempo}}</ref>

On 15 August, Vásquez made his debut as team captain in a 3–0 home victory over [[LR Vicenza|Vicenza]] in the first round of that season's [[2025–26 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]].<ref>https://espndeportes.espn.com/futbol/italia/nota/_/id/15549250/futbol-johan-vasquez-arranca-temporada-capitan-triunfo-genoa</ref> On that same month, it was reported Vásquez extended his contract through 2028.<ref>https://www.soyfutbol.com/en/news/Genoa-Sets-Hefty-Price-Tag-on-Johan-Vasquez-After-Securing-Him-20250830-0055.html</ref>

==International career==
===Youth===
Vásquez began his international career with the [[Mexico national under-23 football team|under-23]] side, featuring at the [[Football at the 2019 Pan American Games – Men's tournament|2019 Pan American Games]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wrsd.lima2019.pe/PAG2019/resPAG2019/pdf/PAG2019/FBL/PAG2019_FBL_C33_FBLMTEAM11------------TEAM01------C_MEX.pdf|title=Football Men – Mexico Team Roster|publisher=Lima 2019|date=29 July 2019|access-date=25 August 2020|archive-date=29 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729232226/https://wrsd.lima2019.pe/PAG2019/resPAG2019/pdf/PAG2019/FBL/PAG2019_FBL_C33_FBLMTEAM11------------TEAM01------C_MEX.pdf|url-status=dead}}</ref> where Mexico won the bronze medal.<ref>{{cite web|title=México rescató el Bronce en Panamericanos tras vencer a Uruguay con muchos apuros|date=8 November 2019 |url=https://www.mediotiempo.com/deportes-olimpicos/juegos-panamericanos/mexico-1-0-uruguay-bronce-tricolor-lima-2019-cronica-video}}</ref> He also participated at the [[2020 CONCACAF Men's Olympic Qualifying Championship|2020 CONCACAF Olympic Qualifying Championship]], scoring one goal in five appearances, where Mexico won the competition. He was included in the tournament's Best XI.<ref name=CONCACAF>{{cite web|title=Ellos son los 4 mexicanos que encabezan el 11 ideal de Concacaf del Preolímpico 2021|date=31 March 2021 |url=https://soyreferee.com/futbolinternacional/Ellos-son-los-4-mexicanos-que-encabezan-el-11-ideal-de-Concacaf-del-Preolimpico-2021-20210331-0016.html}}</ref> Vásquez was subsequently called up to participate in the [[2020 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Revelan lista oficial de la Selección Sub-23 que acudirá a Tokio 2020|date=5 July 2021|url=https://espndeportes.espn.com/futbol/selecciones/nota/_/id/8854207/mexico-sub23-convocatoria-jaime-lozano-tokio-2020}}</ref> He scored Mexico's second goal in a 3–1 victory over Olympic hosts, [[Japan national under-23 football team|Japan]], in the [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament – Knockout stage#Bronze medal match|third-place match]] for the [[bronze medal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/601587|title=Mexico U23 3-1 Japan U23 (Aug 6, 2021) Game Analysis|website=ESPN}}</ref>

===Senior===
On 2 October 2019, under [[Gerardo Martino]], Vásquez made his [[Mexico national football team|senior national team]] debut in a friendly against [[Trinidad & Tobago national football team|Trinidad & Tobago]]. He came on as a substitute replacing [[Paolo Yrizar]] in the 63rd minute in Mexico's 2–0 win.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[ESPN]]|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/lineups?gameId=557649|title=Mexico v Trinidad & Tobago game report|date=2 October 2019}}</ref>

In October 2022, Vásquez was named in Mexico's preliminary 31-man squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]], and in November, he was ultimately included in the final 26-man roster, but did not receive any minutes on the field during the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lista de convocados de la Selección Mexicana al Mundial de Qatar 2022|url=https://www.tvazteca.com/aztecadeportes/lista-oficial-convocados-seleccion-mexicana-mundial-qatar-2022|work=Tvazteca.com|first=Omar|last=Moro|date=14 November 2022|language=Spanish}}</ref>

Vásquez was called up by [[Javier Aguirre]] to participate at the [[2025 CONCACAF Nations League Finals]] and the subsequent [[2025 CONCACAF Gold Cup|Gold Cup]] in which Mexico won both after defeating both [[Panama national football team|Panama]]<ref>https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/723672</ref> and the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]],<ref>https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/45684192/mexico-beats-usmnt-win-10th-gold-cup</ref> respectively. He was included in both tournament's best XI.

